🔹 What is a Server?

A server is:
A system (hardware or software) that provides services, data, or resources to other systems
called clients.

🔹 Simple Meaning

If something:
Receives requests
Processes them
Sends back a response

👉 That is acting as a server.

🔹 Client–Server Example

When you open a website:

Your browser sends request
A server receives it
Server processes it
Server sends response (HTML, JSON, etc.)

So:
Browser = Client
Backend machine = Server

🔹 Is Server Always a Machine?

Not necessarily.

A server can be:

1️⃣ Physical Machine
A computer running 24/7 in a data center.

2️⃣ Virtual Machine (Cloud)
Example:
Amazon Web Services
Microsoft Azure

3️⃣ Software Program
Example:
Apache Tomcat
Nginx

Your Spring Boot app also runs inside a server.

🔹 Types of Servers

Different servers provide different services:

Type	                                             What It Does

Web Server	                                         Serves web pages
Application Server	                                 Runs business logic
Database Server	                                     Stores & manages data
File Server	                                         Stores files
Mail Server	                                         Handles emails

Example database server:
MySQL

When you call a REST API:
Client → Web Server → Application → Database Server → Response → Client

Spring Boot:

Starts embedded Tomcat
Binds it to port 8080 (default)
Loads your controllers
Starts listening for HTTP requests

Now your app is:
👉 Acting as a server.

JVM Process
 ├── Embedded Server (Tomcat)
 ├── Spring IoC Container
 │     ├── Controllers
 │     ├── Services
 │     ├── Repositories
 │     └── Other Beans

Q.Why Is It Outside IoC?

Because:
👉 The server must start before Spring can receive any request.

Think about order of startup:

JVM starts
Spring Boot starts
Embedded Tomcat starts
Tomcat starts listening on port
Tomcat loads Spring’s DispatcherServlet
Now requests can reach Spring

So the server is infrastructure.
Spring IoC is application logic.

🔥 Important Separation of Concerns
Layer	                                             Responsibility

OS	                                                 Runs processes
JVM	                                                 Runs Java code
Tomcat	                                             Handles HTTP
Spring IoC	                                         Manages beans
Your Service	                                     Business logic